DS3 Data Memo

Avriana Allen | 4.24.2020

The Data

This quarter I have decided to work with the U.S. Department of Education’s College Scorecard data. There are two available data sets on their website, the first related to the institutions, the second related to the fields of study. Both are large, the first coming in with over six thousand rows, while the second has two hundred sixteen observations. Currently, the main data set of interest will be the Institutions but I may use the Field of Study as a supplementary data set.

There are several accompanying data dictionaries which are downloadable as a single xlsx file.

The Institutions data set has 1,982 variables. It is likely that many of these categories may be collapsed into larger categories, or ignored for the sake of simplicity.

OMENRUP_FULLTIME_POOLED_SUPP Percentage of full-time students that did not receive an award and whose enrollment status is unknown after leaving this institution within 8 years of entry, pooled in rolling averages and suppressed for small n size
OMENRYP_PARTTIME_POOLED_SUPP Percentage of part-time students that did not receive an award and are still enrolled at this institution 8 years after entry, pooled in rolling averages and suppressed for small n size
OMENRAP_PARTTIME_POOLED_SUPP Percentage of part-time students that did not receive an award and enrolled at another institution after leaving this institution within 8 years of entry, pooled in rolling averages and suppressed for small n size
OMAWDP8_PARTTIME_POOLED_SUPP Percentage of part-time student receiving an award within 8 years of entry, pooled in rolling averages and suppressed for small n size
OMENRUP_PARTTIME_POOLED_SUPP Percentage of part-time students that did not receive an award and whose enrollment status is unknown after leaving this institution within 8 years of entry, pooled in rolling averages and suppressed for small n size
FTFTPCTPELL Percentage of full-time, first-time degree/certificate-seeking undergraduate students awarded a Pell Grant
FTFTPCTFLOAN Percentage of full-time, first-time degree/certificate-seeking undergraduate students awarded a federal loan
UG12MN Unduplicated count of undergraduate students enrolled during a 12 month period
G12MN Unduplicated count of graduate students enrolled during a 12 month period
SCUGFFN Number of full-time, first-time degree/certificate-seeking undergraduate students (denominator for percent full-time, first-time degree/certificate-seeking undergraduates receiving a pell grant or federal student loan)

Data Questions

After looking at the variables available, it would interesting to predict a few different outcomes. Student loan repayment, percentage of specific degrees or mean earnings of students would all be interesting to consider.

However, each of those categories is split into smaller groups such as family income or number of years since enrollment. To work with any of them, I will need to create specific response variable, which depending on the question I choose to answer, may be several categories put together.

This is a survey of more or less all of the colleges in the U.S. which means that it is a population and not a sample. Many of results however, are likely samples. We may be able to make inferences about the population given our ability to randomly sample from it.

If this is possible, it would be interesting to see what traits can be used to predict student debt or earnings as well as seeing what characteristics the colleges with the best and worst earnings have in terms of admission, diversity, etc.

Random Forests or Boosted models might be good for this given the number of categorical variables available. Although other models have not yet been covered, they may also be useful, especially if there are not linear relationships between the response variables and the predictors.

Data Issues

This data set will be a challenge, not only because of the number of variables or decisions that will need to be made concerning which ones to use, but also because of missing values. In the csv form they are listed as NULL which does not carry over well into R.

Another issue to deal with will be how to collapse the variables. It is likely that a lot of regex work with the appropriate data dictionary will be done.
